we've talked about the cerebellum.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:35.770
I want to talk about an area of the brain

01:02:35.770 --> 01:02:39.380
that is rarely discussed
which is the midbrain.

01:02:39.380 --> 01:02:40.213
- Yeah.

01:02:40.213 --> 01:02:42.860
- And for those that don't know,

01:02:42.860 --> 01:02:45.322
the midbrain is an area
beneath the cortex.

01:02:45.322 --> 01:02:46.650
I guess we never really defined cortex

01:02:46.650 --> 01:02:50.690
was kind of the outer layers
or are the outer layers

01:02:50.690 --> 01:02:54.207
of the at least mammalian
brain or human brain.

01:02:54.207 --> 01:02:56.796
But the midbrain is super interesting,

01:02:56.796 --> 01:03:01.796
because it controls a
lot of unconscious stuff,

01:03:02.460 --> 01:03:03.913
reflexes, et cetera.

01:03:04.780 --> 01:03:07.930
And then there's this phenomenon
even called blind sight.

01:03:07.930 --> 01:03:11.020
So could you please tell
us about the midbrain

01:03:11.020 --> 01:03:15.700
about what it does, and
what in the world is sight?

01:03:15.700 --> 01:03:19.550
- Yeah, so there's a lot of pieces there.

01:03:19.550 --> 01:03:20.960
I think the first thing to say is,

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:24.999
if you imagine the nervous
system in your mind's eye,

01:03:24.999 --> 01:03:26.759
you see this big honking brain

01:03:26.759 --> 01:03:30.870
and then there's this little wand

01:03:30.870 --> 01:03:34.570
that dangles down into your
vertical column the spinal cord

01:03:34.570 --> 01:03:36.670
and that's kind of your visual impression.

01:03:37.810 --> 01:03:40.140
What you have to imagine is
starting in the spinal cord

01:03:40.140 --> 01:03:42.567
and working your way up into
this big magnificent brain

01:03:42.567 --> 01:03:46.440
and what you would do
as you enter the skull,

01:03:46.440 --> 01:03:48.970
is get into a little place
where the spinal cord

01:03:48.970 --> 01:03:50.180
kind of thickens out.

01:03:50.180 --> 01:03:54.550
It still has that sort of long,
skinny trunk-like feeling.

01:03:54.550 --> 01:03:56.720
- It's more like a
paddle or a spoon shape.

01:03:56.720 --> 01:03:58.257
- Right, it starts to
spread out a little bit

01:03:58.257 --> 01:04:00.230
and that's 'cause your evolutionists

01:04:00.230 --> 01:04:02.080
packed more interesting goodies in there

01:04:02.080 --> 01:04:05.330
for processing information
and generating movement.

01:04:05.330 --> 01:04:10.330
So beyond that is this tween
brain we were talking about.

01:04:10.557 --> 01:04:13.443
This linker brain with
diencephalon really means

01:04:13.443 --> 01:04:14.850
the between brain.

01:04:14.850 --> 01:04:16.080
- Oh, I thought you said tween.

01:04:16.080 --> 01:04:17.780
- Well, it is, yes.
- No, no, no, between.

01:04:17.780 --> 01:04:18.613
Between.
- Between.

01:04:18.613 --> 01:04:19.780
[indistinct]
- You said tween.

01:04:19.780 --> 01:04:22.250
- Yeah, it's the between,
it's the between brain

01:04:22.250 --> 01:04:24.320
is what the name means.

01:04:24.320 --> 01:04:27.780
It's the linker from the
spinal cord in the periphery

01:04:27.780 --> 01:04:30.107
up to these grand centers of the cortex.

01:04:30.107 --> 01:04:34.267
But this midbrain you're
talking about is the last bit

01:04:34.267 --> 01:04:37.970
of this enlarged sort of spinal
cordy thing in your skull,

01:04:37.970 --> 01:04:40.646
which is really the brain
stem is what we call it.

01:04:40.646 --> 01:04:44.040
The last bit of that before
you get to this relay up

01:04:44.040 --> 01:04:46.990
to the cortex is the midbrain.

01:04:46.990 --> 01:04:49.268
And there's a really
important visual center there,

01:04:49.268 --> 01:04:51.503
it's called the superior colliculus.

01:04:52.350 --> 01:04:54.560
There's a similar center in the brains

01:04:54.560 --> 01:04:58.460
of other vertebrate animals a
frog for example or a lizard,

01:04:58.460 --> 01:05:01.410
would have this is called
the optic tectum there

01:05:01.410 --> 01:05:06.410
but it's a center, then in
these non-mammalian vertebrates,

01:05:08.440 --> 01:05:11.050
is really the main visual center.

01:05:11.050 --> 01:05:13.320
They don't really have what
we would call a visual cortex

01:05:13.320 --> 01:05:15.680
although there's something
sort of like that.

01:05:15.680 --> 01:05:17.570
But this is where most of the action is

01:05:17.570 --> 01:05:19.570
in terms of interpreting visual input

01:05:19.570 --> 01:05:22.473
and organizing behavior around that.

01:05:23.950 --> 01:05:26.440
You can sort of think about this region

01:05:26.440 --> 01:05:28.550
of the brain stem as a reflex center

01:05:28.550 --> 01:05:33.550
that can reorient the
animal's gaze or body

01:05:34.470 --> 01:05:39.410
or maybe even attention to
particular regions of space

01:05:39.410 --> 01:05:41.590
out there around the animal

01:05:41.590 --> 01:05:43.493
and that could be for
all kinds of reasons.

01:05:43.493 --> 01:05:46.303
It might be a predator just
showed up in one corner

01:05:46.303 --> 01:05:48.177
of the forest and you pick that up

01:05:48.177 --> 01:05:49.683
and you're trying to avoid it.

01:05:49.683 --> 01:05:52.400
- Or just any movement.
- Any movement, right?

01:05:52.400 --> 01:05:57.310
It might be that suddenly
something splats on the page

01:05:57.310 --> 01:05:58.184
when you're reading a novel

01:05:58.184 --> 01:06:01.904
and your eye reflexively looks at it.

01:06:01.904 --> 01:06:04.200
You don't have to think
about that, that's a reflex.

01:06:04.200 --> 01:06:07.300
- What if you throw me a ball
but I'm not expecting it?

01:06:07.300 --> 01:06:08.180
- Right.
- And I just reach up

01:06:08.180 --> 01:06:10.800
try and grab it touch it or not.

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:12.320
Is that handled by the midbrain?

01:06:12.320 --> 01:06:14.940
- Well, that's probably not the midbrain

01:06:14.940 --> 01:06:18.300
although by itself, because
it's going to involve

01:06:18.300 --> 01:06:19.710
all these limb movements,

01:06:19.710 --> 01:06:21.513
this movement of your arm and body.

01:06:23.010 --> 01:06:23.890
- What about ducking

01:06:23.890 --> 01:06:25.670
if something's suddenly
thrown in your head?

01:06:25.670 --> 01:06:27.100
- Sure, right, things like that

01:06:27.100 --> 01:06:28.990
will certainly have a brainstem component,

01:06:28.990 --> 01:06:32.323
a midbrain component,
something looms and you duck.

01:06:34.010 --> 01:06:36.150
It may not be the superior colliculus

01:06:36.150 --> 01:06:37.010
we're talking about now,

01:06:37.010 --> 01:06:39.150
it might be another part
of the visual midbrain.

01:06:39.150 --> 01:06:41.690
But these are centers that emerged early

01:06:41.690 --> 01:06:43.920
in the evolution of brains like ours

01:06:43.920 --> 01:06:46.291
to handle complicated visual events

01:06:46.291 --> 01:06:48.900
that have significance for the animal

01:06:48.900 --> 01:06:51.630
in terms of space, where is it in space?

01:06:51.630 --> 01:06:53.020
And in fact, this same center

01:06:53.020 --> 01:06:56.210
actually gets input from all
kinds of other sensory systems

01:06:56.210 --> 01:06:58.880
that take information
from the external world

01:06:58.880 --> 01:07:00.590
from particular locations

01:07:00.590 --> 01:07:03.540
and where you might want to
either avoid or approach things

01:07:03.540 --> 01:07:05.338
according to their significance to you.

01:07:05.338 --> 01:07:08.700
So you get input from the touch system,

01:07:08.700 --> 01:07:11.530
you get input from the auditory system.

01:07:11.530 --> 01:07:13.490
I work for a while in rattlesnakes,

01:07:13.490 --> 01:07:17.315
they get input from a
part of their warm sensors

01:07:17.315 --> 01:07:20.058
on their face, they're in
these little pits on the face.

01:07:20.058 --> 01:07:22.104
- To work on baby rattlesnakes, right?

01:07:22.104 --> 01:07:23.589
- They were adults.

01:07:23.589 --> 01:07:25.670
- Oh, I wasn't trying
to diminish the danger.

01:07:25.670 --> 01:07:27.290
I thought for some reason
they were little ones.

01:07:27.290 --> 01:07:28.507
- No.
- Why in the world

01:07:28.507 --> 01:07:30.280
would you work on rattlesnakes?

01:07:30.280 --> 01:07:33.770
- Well, because they have a version

01:07:33.770 --> 01:07:35.940
of an extra receptive sensory system

01:07:35.940 --> 01:07:39.020
that is they're looking out into the world

01:07:39.020 --> 01:07:41.100
using a completely
different set of sensors.

01:07:41.100 --> 01:07:42.310
They're using the same sensors

01:07:42.310 --> 01:07:43.990
that would feel the warmth on your face

01:07:43.990 --> 01:07:45.569
if you stood in front of a bonfire.

01:07:45.569 --> 01:07:48.410
Except, evolution has given them

01:07:48.410 --> 01:07:49.970
this very nice specialized system

01:07:49.970 --> 01:07:52.210
that lets them image where
the heat's coming from.

01:07:52.210 --> 01:07:53.920
You can sort of do that anyway, right?

01:07:53.920 --> 01:07:56.260
If you walk around the fire,

01:07:56.260 --> 01:07:59.590
you can feel where the
fire is from the heat

01:07:59.590 --> 01:08:00.570
hitting your face.

01:08:00.570 --> 01:08:04.380
- Is that the primary way
in which they detect prey?

01:08:04.380 --> 01:08:06.710
- It's one of one of the major ways.

01:08:06.710 --> 01:08:09.140
And in fact, they use vision as well

01:08:09.140 --> 01:08:11.140
and they bring these two systems together

01:08:11.140 --> 01:08:13.810
in the same place in this tectum regions

01:08:13.810 --> 01:08:14.856
brain stem, midbrain.

01:08:14.856 --> 01:08:17.560
- What's the tongue jutting
about when the snakes?

01:08:17.560 --> 01:08:19.130
- That I don't know.

01:08:19.130 --> 01:08:20.770
That may be old factory, they're maybe.

01:08:20.770 --> 01:08:21.954
- They're sniffing the
air with their tongue?

01:08:21.954 --> 01:08:23.580
- Yeah, there may be, 'cause.

01:08:23.580 --> 01:08:27.080
- On our drive you told me that
flies actually taste things

01:08:27.080 --> 01:08:28.590
with their feet.
- They do, yeah.

01:08:28.590 --> 01:08:29.423
- That's so weird.

01:08:29.423 --> 01:08:33.320
- Yeah, they have taste receptors
and lots of funny places.

01:08:33.320 --> 01:08:34.960
I want to pause here just for one second

01:08:34.960 --> 01:08:36.540
before we get back into the midbrain.

01:08:36.540 --> 01:08:40.160
I think what's so interesting
in all seriousness

01:08:40.160 --> 01:08:45.080
about taste receptors
on feet, heat sensors,

01:08:45.080 --> 01:08:48.500
tongues shutting out of snakes and vision

01:08:48.500 --> 01:08:50.760
and all this integration is that,

01:08:50.760 --> 01:08:55.060
it really speaks to the fact
that all these sensory neurons

01:08:55.060 --> 01:08:59.750
are trying to gather information
and stuff it into a system

01:08:59.750 --> 01:09:03.280
that can make meaningful
decisions and actions.

01:09:03.280 --> 01:09:05.140
And that it really doesn't
matter whether or not

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:08.550
it's coming from eyes or ears
or nose or bottoms of feet,

01:09:08.550 --> 01:09:11.500
because in the end, it's
just electricity flowing in.

01:09:11.500 --> 01:09:14.920
And so it sounds like it's
placed on each animal,

01:09:14.920 --> 01:09:17.360
it always feels weird
to call fly an animal.

01:09:17.360 --> 01:09:20.453
But they are creatures, they are animals.

01:09:21.410 --> 01:09:23.780
It's placed in different
locations on different animals

01:09:23.780 --> 01:09:26.527
depending on the particular
needs of that animal.

01:09:26.527 --> 01:09:29.160
- Right, but how much more powerful

01:09:29.160 --> 01:09:32.870
if the nervous systems
can also cross-correlate

01:09:32.870 --> 01:09:34.950
across sensory systems?

01:09:34.950 --> 01:09:38.140
So if you've got a weak signal
from one sensory system,

01:09:38.140 --> 01:09:39.980
you're not quite sure
there's something there.

01:09:39.980 --> 01:09:43.020
And a weak signal from
an another sensory system

01:09:43.020 --> 01:09:44.800
that's telling you the same locations

01:09:44.800 --> 01:09:46.360
is a little bit interesting.

01:09:46.360 --> 01:09:47.780
There might be something there

01:09:47.780 --> 01:09:50.530
if you've got those two together
you've got corroboration.

01:09:50.530 --> 01:09:53.140
Your brain now says it's much more likely

01:09:53.140 --> 01:09:56.890
that that's going to be something
worth paying attention to.

01:09:56.890 --> 01:09:59.600
- Right, so maybe I'm feeling some heat

01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:01.180
on one side of my face

01:10:02.280 --> 01:10:05.560
and I also smell something
baking in the oven.

01:10:05.560 --> 01:10:06.690
- Right.
- So now there's,

01:10:06.690 --> 01:10:08.850
it's neither is particularly
strong, but as you said,

01:10:08.850 --> 01:10:10.060
there's some corroboration.

01:10:10.060 --> 01:10:11.340
- Right.
And that corroboration

01:10:11.340 --> 01:10:12.510
is occurring in the midbrain.

