So what appears to have been the case

01:35:13.490 --> 01:35:16.390
and this has been confirmed in other ways

01:35:16.390 --> 01:35:19.150
by imaging experiments in humans is that,

01:35:19.150 --> 01:35:22.020
in people who are blind
from very early in birth,

01:35:22.020 --> 01:35:25.280
the visual cortex gets repurposed

01:35:25.280 --> 01:35:28.770
as a center for processing
tactile information.

01:35:28.770 --> 01:35:31.560
And especially if you train
to be a good braille reader,

01:35:31.560 --> 01:35:35.730
you're actually reallocating
somehow that real estate

01:35:35.730 --> 01:35:37.131
to your fingertips.

01:35:37.131 --> 01:35:40.260
A part of the cortex that
should be listening to the eyes.

01:35:40.260 --> 01:35:42.450
So that's an extreme level of plasticity.

01:35:42.450 --> 01:35:45.760
But what it shows, is the visual cortex

01:35:45.760 --> 01:35:48.770
is kind of a general
purpose processing machine,

01:35:48.770 --> 01:35:51.527
it's good at spatial information

01:35:51.527 --> 01:35:55.070
and the skin of your fingers
is just another spatial sense

01:35:55.070 --> 01:35:59.630
and deprived of any other input
the brain seems smart enough

01:35:59.630 --> 01:36:02.550
if you want to put it
that way to rewire itself

01:36:02.550 --> 01:36:05.660
to use that real estate
for something useful,

01:36:05.660 --> 01:36:07.163
in this case, reading braille.

01:36:08.080 --> 01:36:10.380
- Incredible, somewhat
tragic, but incredible.

01:36:10.380 --> 01:36:12.300
At least in that case tragic, yeah.

01:36:12.300 --> 01:36:14.110
- Very informative.
- Very informative.

01:36:14.110 --> 01:36:15.640
And of course it can go the other way too.

01:36:15.640 --> 01:36:16.473
- Right.

01:36:16.473 --> 01:36:20.220
- Where people can gain function
in particular modalities

01:36:20.220 --> 01:36:22.690
like improved hearing or tactile function

01:36:22.690 --> 01:36:24.440
in the absence of vision.
- Right.

01:36:26.950 --> 01:36:30.470
- Tell us about connectomes,
we hear about genomes,

01:36:30.470 --> 01:36:34.324
proteomes, microbiomes, ohms, ohms, ohms

01:36:34.324 --> 01:36:36.940
these days.
- Yeah.

01:36:36.940 --> 01:36:39.400
- What's a connectome
and why is it valuable?

01:36:39.400 --> 01:36:42.760
- Yeah, so the connectome
actually now has two meanings.

01:36:42.760 --> 01:36:47.422
So I'll only refer to one
that is my passion right now.

01:36:47.422 --> 01:36:50.140
And that is really trying
to understand the structure

01:36:50.140 --> 01:36:55.140
of nervous tissue at a scale
that's very, very fine.

01:36:58.130 --> 01:36:59.200
- Smaller than a millimeter.

01:36:59.200 --> 01:37:02.680
- Way smaller than a
millimeter, a nanometer or less,

01:37:02.680 --> 01:37:04.573
as that's 1,000 times smaller,

01:37:05.966 --> 01:37:10.966
or it's actually a million times smaller.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:14.100
So really, really tiny

01:37:14.100 --> 01:37:16.090
on the scale of individual synapses

01:37:16.090 --> 01:37:17.300
between individual neurons

01:37:17.300 --> 01:37:20.440
or even smaller like the
individual synaptic vesicles

01:37:20.440 --> 01:37:22.260
containing little packets
of neurotransmitter

01:37:22.260 --> 01:37:24.710
they're going to get it
released to allow one neuron

01:37:24.710 --> 01:37:26.370
to communicate to the next.

01:37:26.370 --> 01:37:31.370
So very, very fine, but
the notion here is that,

01:37:33.130 --> 01:37:38.130
you're doing this section after
section at very fine scale.

01:37:39.270 --> 01:37:41.860
So in theory what you have
is a complete description

01:37:41.860 --> 01:37:46.280
of a chunk of nervous
tissue that is so complete

01:37:46.280 --> 01:37:48.060
that if you took enough time to identify

01:37:48.060 --> 01:37:49.860
where the boundaries of all the cells are,

01:37:49.860 --> 01:37:52.360
you could come up with
a complete description

01:37:52.360 --> 01:37:55.780
of the synaptic wiring of
that chunk of nervous tissue

01:37:55.780 --> 01:37:56.820
because you have a complete description

01:37:56.820 --> 01:37:58.990
of where all the cells are
and where all the synapses

01:37:58.990 --> 01:38:00.400
between where all the cells are.

01:38:00.400 --> 01:38:02.710
So now you essentially
have a wiring diagram

01:38:02.710 --> 01:38:04.690
of this complicated piece of tissue.

01:38:04.690 --> 01:38:08.560
So the omics part is
the exhaustiveness of it

01:38:08.560 --> 01:38:10.290
rather than looking at
a couple of synapses

01:38:10.290 --> 01:38:13.890
that are interesting to you
from two different cell types.

01:38:13.890 --> 01:38:17.770
You're looking at all the
synapses of all of the cell types

01:38:17.770 --> 01:38:22.690
which of course is this massive
avalanche of data, right?

01:38:22.690 --> 01:38:24.340
- So in genetics, you have genetics

01:38:24.340 --> 01:38:25.380
and then you have genomics

01:38:25.380 --> 01:38:27.050
which is the idea of
getting the whole genome.

01:38:27.050 --> 01:38:27.883
- All of it.

01:38:27.883 --> 01:38:30.910
- And we don't really have an
analogous word for genetics,

01:38:30.910 --> 01:38:33.091
but it would be connectivity
and [indistinct].

01:38:33.091 --> 01:38:38.070
- Right.
[indistinct]

01:38:38.070 --> 01:38:40.330
- Right, so it's wanting it all

01:38:40.330 --> 01:38:42.680
and of course it's crazy ambitious,

01:38:42.680 --> 01:38:45.240
but that's where it gets fun.

01:38:45.240 --> 01:38:48.530
Really it's a use of electron microscopy,

01:38:48.530 --> 01:38:53.480
a very high resolution
microscopic imaging system

01:38:53.480 --> 01:38:56.900
on a new scale with way more payoff

01:38:56.900 --> 01:38:58.680
in terms of understanding the connectivity

01:38:58.680 --> 01:39:01.530
of the nervous system
and it's just emerging,

01:39:01.530 --> 01:39:04.290
but I really think it's going
to revolutionize the field

01:39:04.290 --> 01:39:07.230
because we're going to be
able to query these circuits

01:39:07.230 --> 01:39:09.900
how do they actually do
it, look at the hardware

01:39:09.900 --> 01:39:12.430
in a way that's never
been possible before.

01:39:12.430 --> 01:39:14.550
- The the way that I
describe this to people

01:39:14.550 --> 01:39:17.300
is if you were to take a
chunk of kind of cooked

01:39:18.380 --> 01:39:20.220
but cold spaghetti.
- Right.

01:39:20.220 --> 01:39:23.830
- And slice it up very thin
you're trying to connect up

01:39:23.830 --> 01:39:28.100
each image of each slice of
the edge of the spaghetti

01:39:28.100 --> 01:39:30.070
as figure out which ropes of spaghetti

01:39:30.070 --> 01:39:30.903
belong to which.

01:39:30.903 --> 01:39:32.230
- And have a complete description

01:39:32.230 --> 01:39:33.460
of where this piece of spaghetti

01:39:33.460 --> 01:39:34.466
touches that piece of spaghetti

01:39:34.466 --> 01:39:36.740
is there's something
special there obviously.

01:39:36.740 --> 01:39:38.690
- Meat sauces and all the other cell types

01:39:38.690 --> 01:39:43.690
and the pesto where it all
is around the spaghetti

01:39:43.760 --> 01:39:45.580
because those are the other
cells, the blood vessels

01:39:45.580 --> 01:39:47.030
and the glial cells.

01:39:47.030 --> 01:39:50.700
And so, what's it good for?

01:39:50.700 --> 01:39:55.364
Maps are great, I always think
of connectomics and genomics

01:39:55.364 --> 01:39:59.070
and proteomics, et cetera as necessary,

01:39:59.070 --> 01:40:01.030
but not sufficient.
- Right.

01:40:01.030 --> 01:40:03.840
Right, so I mean in many cases
what you do is you go out

01:40:03.840 --> 01:40:05.890
and probe the function

01:40:05.890 --> 01:40:07.990
and you understand how the
brain does the function

01:40:07.990 --> 01:40:10.920
by finding neurons that seem to be firing

01:40:10.920 --> 01:40:14.090
in association with this
function that you're observing.

01:40:14.090 --> 01:40:15.700
And little by little
you're work your way in

01:40:15.700 --> 01:40:17.300
and now you want to know
what the conductivity is

01:40:17.300 --> 01:40:19.730
maybe the anatomy could help you.

01:40:19.730 --> 01:40:21.550
But this connectomics approach

01:40:21.550 --> 01:40:23.660
or at least the serial electron microscopy

01:40:23.660 --> 01:40:27.230
reconstruction of neurons approach,

01:40:27.230 --> 01:40:29.938
really is allowing us to frame questions

01:40:29.938 --> 01:40:33.450
starting from the anatomy and saying,

01:40:33.450 --> 01:40:35.130
I see a synaptic circuit here,

01:40:35.130 --> 01:40:38.010
my prediction would be that
these cell types would interact

01:40:38.010 --> 01:40:40.160
in a particular way, is that right?

01:40:40.160 --> 01:40:42.200
And then you can go and
probe the physiology

01:40:42.200 --> 01:40:43.760
and you might be right
or you might be wrong.

01:40:43.760 --> 01:40:46.830
But more often than not,
it looks like the structure

01:40:46.830 --> 01:40:48.780
is pointing us in the right direction.

01:40:48.780 --> 01:40:53.510
So in my case, I'm using this
to try to understand a circuit

01:40:53.510 --> 01:40:56.150
that is involved in this
image stabilization network

01:40:56.150 --> 01:41:00.250
we're talking about, keeping
things stable on the retina

01:41:00.250 --> 01:41:02.540
and this thing will only respond

01:41:02.540 --> 01:41:04.307
at certain speeds of motion.

01:41:04.307 --> 01:41:06.040
These cells in the circuit

01:41:06.040 --> 01:41:08.867
like slow motion they won't
respond to fast motion,

01:41:08.867 --> 01:41:10.330
how does that come about?

01:41:10.330 --> 01:41:14.040
Well, I was able to probe the circuitry,

01:41:14.040 --> 01:41:15.500
I knew what my cells looked like,

01:41:15.500 --> 01:41:17.116
I could see which other
cells were talking to it,

01:41:17.116 --> 01:41:19.080
I could categorize all the cells

01:41:19.080 --> 01:41:20.580
that might be the players here

01:41:20.580 --> 01:41:23.540
that are involved in this
mechanism of tuning the thing

01:41:23.540 --> 01:41:25.530
for slow speeds,

01:41:25.530 --> 01:41:27.870
and then we said it looks
like it's that cell type

01:41:27.870 --> 01:41:30.814
and we went and looked
and the data bore that up.

01:41:30.814 --> 01:41:33.340
But the anatomy drove the search

01:41:33.340 --> 01:41:34.510
for the particular cell type

01:41:34.510 --> 01:41:36.890
because we could see it
connected in the right place

01:41:36.890 --> 01:41:38.020
to the right cells.

01:41:38.020 --> 01:41:40.090
So creates the hypothesis

01:41:40.090 --> 01:41:42.620
that lets you go query the physiology,

01:41:42.620 --> 01:41:44.010
but it can go the other way as well.

01:41:44.010 --> 01:41:46.120
So it's always the synergy
between these functional

01:41:46.120 --> 01:41:51.120
and structural approaches
it gives you the most lift.

01:41:51.290 --> 01:41:53.680
But in many cases,

01:41:53.680 --> 01:41:56.650
the anatomy has been a little
bit the weak sister in this.

01:41:56.650 --> 01:41:59.120
The structure trying
to work out the diagram

01:41:59.120 --> 01:42:00.900
because we haven't had the methods.

01:42:00.900 --> 01:42:02.680
Now the methods exist

01:42:02.680 --> 01:42:05.740
and this whole field is
expanding very quickly,

01:42:05.740 --> 01:42:07.815
because people want these circuit diagrams

01:42:07.815 --> 01:42:10.910
for the particular part
of the nervous system

01:42:10.910 --> 01:42:12.410
that they're working on.

01:42:12.410 --> 01:42:14.310
If you don't know the cell
types and the connections,

01:42:14.310 --> 01:42:17.420
how do you really understand
how the machine works?

01:42:17.420 --> 01:42:18.850
- Yeah, what I love about is,

01:42:18.850 --> 01:42:19.877
we don't know what we don't know.

01:42:19.877 --> 01:42:20.710
- Right.

01:42:20.710 --> 01:42:23.890
- And scientists we don't ask
questions, we pose hypotheses.

01:42:23.890 --> 01:42:26.260
Hypotheses being of course some prediction

01:42:26.260 --> 01:42:28.900
that you wager your time on basically.

01:42:28.900 --> 01:42:30.980
- Right.
- And it either turns out

01:42:30.980 --> 01:42:35.930
to be true or not true,
but if you don't know

01:42:35.930 --> 01:42:37.610
that a particular cell type is there,

01:42:37.610 --> 01:42:42.610
you could never in any
configuration of life or a career

01:42:43.960 --> 01:42:47.790
or exploration of a nervous
system wager a hypothesis

01:42:47.790 --> 01:42:49.340
because you didn't know it was there.

01:42:49.340 --> 01:42:50.460
So this allows you to say ah,

01:42:50.460 --> 01:42:52.950
there's a little interesting
little connection

01:42:52.950 --> 01:42:55.030
between this cell that
I know is interesting

01:42:55.030 --> 01:42:57.640
in another cell that's a little
mysterious but interesting,

01:42:57.640 --> 01:43:00.080
I'm going to hypothesize
that it's doing blank,

01:43:00.080 --> 01:43:01.310
blank and blank and go test that.

01:43:01.310 --> 01:43:03.450
And in the absence of these connectomes,

01:43:03.450 --> 01:43:05.150
you would never know that
that cell was lurking there

01:43:05.150 --> 01:43:06.623
in the shadows.

01:43:06.623 --> 01:43:08.300
- Right, right, yeah.

01:43:08.300 --> 01:43:09.650
And if you're just trying to understand

01:43:09.650 --> 01:43:13.884
how information flows through
this biological machine,

01:43:13.884 --> 01:43:16.370
you want to know where things are.

01:43:16.370 --> 01:43:18.640
Neurotransmitters are
dumped out of the terminals

01:43:18.640 --> 01:43:21.890
of one cell and they
diffuse across the space

01:43:21.890 --> 01:43:24.285
between the two cells which
is kind of a liquidy space

01:43:24.285 --> 01:43:26.710
and they hit some receptors
on the postsynaptic cell

01:43:26.710 --> 01:43:28.063
and they have some impact.

01:43:28.920 --> 01:43:31.410
Sometimes that's not
through a regular synapse,

01:43:31.410 --> 01:43:33.100
sometimes it's through a neuromodulator

01:43:33.100 --> 01:43:35.840
like you often talk about on your podcast

01:43:35.840 --> 01:43:36.673
that are sort of.

01:43:36.673 --> 01:43:38.220
- Dopamine.
- Dopamine, exactly.

01:43:38.220 --> 01:43:40.530
Oozing into the space between the cells

01:43:40.530 --> 01:43:42.700
and it may be acting at some distance

01:43:42.700 --> 01:43:45.030
far from where it was released, right?

01:43:45.030 --> 01:43:47.200
But if you don't know where
the release is happening

01:43:47.200 --> 01:43:48.140
and where other things

01:43:48.140 --> 01:43:49.870
are that might respond to that release

01:43:49.870 --> 01:43:52.162
you're groping around in the dark.

01:43:52.162 --> 01:43:54.110
- Well, I love that you are doing this

01:43:54.110 --> 01:43:58.420
and I have to share
with the listeners that,

01:43:58.420 --> 01:44:00.113
the first time I ever met David

01:44:00.113 --> 01:44:03.230
and every time I've ever
met with him in-person

01:44:03.230 --> 01:44:06.240
at least at his laboratory at Brown,

01:44:06.240 --> 01:44:08.750
he was in his office, door closed,

01:44:08.750 --> 01:44:10.937
drawing neurons and their connections.

01:44:10.937 --> 01:44:11.770
[laughs]

01:44:11.770 --> 01:44:13.160
And this is somewhat unusual

01:44:13.160 --> 01:44:16.930
for somebody who's a endowed
full professor or chairman

01:44:16.930 --> 01:44:19.240
of the department et cetera for many years

01:44:19.240 --> 01:44:20.910
to be doing the hands-on work.

01:44:20.910 --> 01:44:22.770
Typically, that's the stuff
that's done by technicians

01:44:22.770 --> 01:44:24.180
or graduate students or postdocs.

01:44:24.180 --> 01:44:26.090
But I think it's fair to say

01:44:26.090 --> 01:44:29.760
that you really love
looking at nervous systems

01:44:29.760 --> 01:44:33.180
and drawing the accurate renditions

01:44:33.180 --> 01:44:35.590
of how those nervous systems are organized

01:44:35.590 --> 01:44:37.330
and thinking about how they work.

01:44:37.330 --> 01:44:38.810
- Yeah, it's pure joy for me.

01:44:38.810 --> 01:44:41.225
I mean, I'm a very visual
person, my wife is an artist,

01:44:41.225 --> 01:44:43.550
we look a lot of art together

01:44:43.550 --> 01:44:47.580
just the forms of things are
gorgeous in their own right.

01:44:47.580 --> 01:44:51.290
But to know that the form
is in a sense the function

01:44:51.290 --> 01:44:55.560
that the architecture of the connectivity

01:44:55.560 --> 01:44:59.470
is how the computation happens
in the brain at some level

01:44:59.470 --> 01:45:02.850
even though we don't fully
understand that in most contexts,

01:45:02.850 --> 01:45:04.978
gives me great joy 'cause
I'm working on something

01:45:04.978 --> 01:45:09.499
that's both visually beautiful
but also deeply beautiful

01:45:09.499 --> 01:45:14.499
in a sort of a higher
sort of knowledge context,

01:45:15.389 --> 01:45:16.750
what is it all about.

01:45:16.750 --> 01:45:20.040
- I love it, well, as a final question,

01:45:20.040 --> 01:45:22.520
I get asked very often about how people

01:45:22.520 --> 01:45:24.183
should learn about neuroscience,

01:45:25.360 --> 01:45:28.160
or how they should go about
pursuing maybe an education

01:45:28.160 --> 01:45:30.330
in neuroscience if they're
at that stage of their life

01:45:30.330 --> 01:45:34.070
or that's appropriate for
their current trajectory.

01:45:34.070 --> 01:45:36.936
Do you have any advice to
young people, old people,

01:45:36.936 --> 01:45:39.730
anything in between about how to learn

01:45:39.730 --> 01:45:42.520
about the nervous system more
maybe in a more formal way?

01:45:42.520 --> 01:45:43.890
I mean obviously, we have our podcast,

01:45:43.890 --> 01:45:46.810
there are other sources of
neuroscience information

01:45:46.810 --> 01:45:48.610
out there, but for the young person

01:45:48.610 --> 01:45:51.610
who thinks they want to
understand the brain,

01:45:51.610 --> 01:45:55.120
they want to learn about the
brain, what should we tell them?

01:45:55.120 --> 01:45:56.370
- Well, that's a great question.

01:45:56.370 --> 01:45:57.880
And there's so many sources out there.

01:45:57.880 --> 01:45:58.950
It's almost a question

01:45:58.950 --> 01:46:01.723
of how do you deal with this
avalanche of information

01:46:01.723 --> 01:46:04.635
out there, I think your podcast
is a great way for people

01:46:04.635 --> 01:46:08.250
to learn more about the nervous
system in an accessible way.

01:46:08.250 --> 01:46:09.760
But there's so much stuff out there

01:46:09.760 --> 01:46:10.593
and it's not just that.

01:46:10.593 --> 01:46:13.870
I mean, the resources are
becoming more and more available

01:46:13.870 --> 01:46:18.580
for average folks to participate
in neuroscience research

01:46:18.580 --> 01:46:19.413
on some level.

01:46:19.413 --> 01:46:21.108
There's this famous Eyewire
project of Sebastian.

01:46:21.108 --> 01:46:23.260
- Oh yeah, maybe you let us about Eyewire.

01:46:23.260 --> 01:46:26.243
- Yeah, so that's connectomics
and that's a situation

01:46:26.243 --> 01:46:29.210
